---
description: agentkit authoring principles (context architecture)
globs:
  - .agentkit/**
alwaysApply: false
---

How agentkit content (skills, instructions, subagents, commands) is authored: optimize for
**token-efficient progressive disclosure**, and apply `dev-principles` to the content itself - the least
content that does the job.

- **Least content.** The best skill is the one you don't write. Question whether a new skill, instruction,
  reference, or section needs to exist; reuse or extend an existing one before adding a file; cut every
  word, bullet, and example that does not earn its place.
- **Tier it.** Routing metadata (name + description) is always loaded - keep it tiny. Bodies load on
  trigger (keep skills under 250 lines, hard cap 500). References load on demand (one level deep; add a
  Table of Contents when over 100 lines).
- **Order for attention.** Put the summary and key triggers first, critical "must-do" steps and a
  `Gotchas` section last; the middle gets the least attention ("Lost in the Middle").
- **Write pre-compressed; strong verbs, no clutter (Zinsser / Hemingway / caveman).** Terse, third
  person, assume model competence; lead with the verb and cut every word that does not change meaning.
  - Prefer base verbs over nominalizations (`make a decision` -> `decide`); the same rule names skills.
  - Kill clutter and hedges: `in order to` -> `to`; drop `very`, `really`, `simply`, `just`,
    `basically`, `actually`, `it is important to`, `please`, `note that`. Enforced by `prose-clutter`.
  - One idea per sentence; short declaratives over compound clauses; numbered steps over prose.
  - Prefer the short common word; concrete heuristics at the "right altitude"; no boilerplate.
- **Name `<domain>-<verb>`.** Use the shortest concrete imperative verb for the action; use a
  recognizable noun only where no clean verb exists (e.g. `design-accessibility`). The domain prefix
  namespaces shared verbs (`develop-review` vs `qa-review`). Avoid `-ing` gerunds (`prefer review, not
  reviewing`); enforced by `name-gerund`.
- **Plain ASCII punctuation.** No em dashes (`U+2014`); use a comma, semicolon, colon, or a spaced hyphen.
  In a YAML `description`, avoid a colon-space (it breaks frontmatter parsing); a comma or hyphen is safe.
  Enforced by the `em-dash` rule.
- **Descriptions are routers.** Say WHAT it does and WHEN to use it (and when not), ≤200 chars.
- **Mind the budget.** Total skill metadata must stay under ~16KB or skills get hidden.
- **One home per skill.** A skill lives only in `.claude/skills/<name>/`; Copilot and Cursor auto-discover
  it and Junie imports it - never hand-mirror it into `.github/agents/` or `.junie/skills/`. A subagent or
  skill body is the **real prompt/procedure**, never a redirect ("see…/read… and follow"). Triggers may
  read when / after / before.
- **No in-context boilerplate.** State a fact once at the right tier - don't stamp "generated/do-not-edit"
  banners on every file (tag generated paths in `.gitattributes` instead).
- **Cite only what an agent would open.** A URL earns its place in agent-facing content only if an agent
  would need it to do the task - a spec it works against, a tool's rules/audit page, canonical docs for
  exact or changing details. Drop pure provenance (blogs, cheat-sheets, topic/landing pages) whose
  guidance is already distilled into the body. Surviving citations live in a `## Sources` or reference
  doc, never inline or in routing metadata.
